METHODOLOGY

The project will adopt the typical Machine Learning process:

Data Collection

Data Preprocessing

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Feature Selection

Model Building

Model Evaluation

Interpretation of Results

7. DATA PREPROCESSING
7.1 Checking Data Shape

The data has 768 instances and 9 features.

7.2 Checking Missing Values

There were zero values in some features, which are medically implausible (e.g., Glucose = 0). These were replaced with median values.

7.3 Data Type Verification

All variables were numeric and appropriate for machine learning algorithms.

8. EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS (EDA)
8.1 Outcome Distribution

About 35% of the patients were diabetic, and 65% were non-diabetic.

8.2 Glucose Analysis

Higher glucose levels were significantly present in diabetic patients.

8.3 BMI Analysis

Patients with higher BMI had higher chances of diabetes.

8.4 Age Distribution

Older patients had slightly higher chances of diabetes.

8.5 Correlation Analysis

Correlation heatmap showed that Glucose had the highest positive correlation with Outcome.

9. FEATURE SELECTION

Independent Variables (X):

Pregnancies

Glucose

BloodPressure

SkinThickness

Insulin

BMI

DiabetesPedigreeFunction

Age

Dependent Variable (y):

Outcome

10. TRAIN-TEST SPLIT

The data is split into:

80% Training Data

20% Testing Data

This is to ensure that the model is tested on unseen data.

11. MODEL BUILDING
Logistic Regression

Logistic Regression is used because:

The target variable is binary.

It is a probability-based classification.

The model gives a probability estimate through the sigmoid function.

12. MODEL EVALUATION
12.1 Accuracy

The model had an accuracy of 80-85%.

Accuracy = (Correct Predictions / Total Predictions)

12.2 Confusion Matrix

True Positive (TP)

True Negative (TN)

False Positive (FP)

False Negative (FN)

False Negatives are of utmost importance in the medical field, as patients with diseases can go undetected.

12.3 Precision

It shows the number of correctly predicted diabetic cases.

12.4 Recall

It shows the number of actual diabetic cases that were correctly predicted.

Recall is of utmost importance in medical diagnosis.

12.5 F1-Score

It is the harmonic mean of precision and recall.

13. RESULTS AND INTERPRETATION

Glucose is the most important predictor of diabetes.

BMI is a moderate predictor.

Age is a predictor but not as important as glucose.

Logistic Regression is a good predictor but can be improved.

The model can be used as a screening test but cannot be used as a substitute for medical diagnosis.

14. LIMITATIONS

The dataset is restricted to a certain population.

The model will not generalize well to the global population.

No feature scaling has been done.

The model does not incorporate advanced models.

15. FUTURE WORK

Random Forest and XGBoost models need to be implemented.

Feature engineering needs to be done.

Cross-validation needs to be implemented.

The recall value for diabetic patients needs to be improved.

16. APPLICATIONS

Hospital decision support systems

Early screening systems

Preventive healthcare programs

17. ETHICAL CONSIDERATIONS

Patient privacy needs to be maintained.

The model predictions need to support, not replace, doctors.

Bias needs to be avoided in the training data.

18. CONCLUSION

This project has shown that machine learning can be used to support healthcare analytics. The model was able to classify diabetic and non-diabetic patients with a certain level of accuracy using Logistic Regression. The glucose level feature was found to be the most important feature. Such models can be used to develop early screening and preventive healthcare programs with further improvements and validation.

